US 101 was established in California by the [[American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials|American Association of State Highway Officials]] (AASHO) in the 1920s. The first [[Traffic sign|trailblazer sign]]s for the newly-commissioned route popped up between San Diego to Los Angeles in January 1928.


As the ''[[Knoxville News Sentinel]]'' noted, the numerical selection for US 101 proved problematic in the early onset. Under AASHO's rules, U.S. Routes with triple-digits are implied to be auxiliary to the main long-distance routes, which typically contain single or double-digits. In the case of US 101, it would have had been a supplementary route for [[U.S. Route 1|US 1]], which currently lies on the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], but it was logically the next available [[odd number]] west of [[U.S. Route 99|US 99]]. To circumvent the issue, the number "101" has been treated as two digits instead of three: a "[[10 (number)|10]]" and a "[[one|1]]".
